div.p:
It is well known that synthetic fiber ropes behave as both the viscous and the elastic materials depending on loading rate and loading history. Besides viscoelastic properties of the ropes themselves, the mechanical properties of the rope are also affected by construction geometry of the ropes themselves either twisting or braiding methods. Both the viscoelasticity and construction geometry of the rope play vital role in elongation behavior of the rope. For example, Flory etÂ al. (


  2004


) had defined, measured, and calculated the elongation of synthetic fiber rope in term of material and constructional elongations in experiment and computer modeling. In addition, they confirmed that constructional elongation is mainly caused during the first loading. Davies etÂ al. (


  2000


) found that the permanent elongation is a combination of material and rope constructional elongations. Loading history has great influence on mechanical properties of the ropes, for example, Davies etÂ al. (


  2006


) found that there is large difference between virgin ropes and bedding-in (preload treatment) rope in term of load-strain curves obtained from static tensile testing. Preload treatment is the loading process used to reduce the constructional elongation and stabilize the mechanical properties of the rope. Weller etÂ al. (


  2014


) concluded that preload treatment has great influence on mechanical property of synthetic fiber rope. Casey and Banfield (


  2003


) and Casey etÂ al. (


  2000


) found that preload treatment that thousands cycles of tensile loading could fully stabilize the rope. It was also noted that 100 cycles of tensile loading probably sufficient for stabilizing the rope. They also confirmed that when the preloaded rope is fully stabilized, the rope behaves almost as elastic material. On the other hand, McKenna etÂ al. (


  2004


) stated that the rope behaves as viscous material for the first cycle of the loading even the rope is fully stabilized after the preload treatment. After few cycles, the rope behaves as elastic material. However, they did not clarify the cause of viscous behavior presented in the stabilized rope which may involve in changing the construction geometry of the rope or material itself.

There are many guidelines for preload treatment of synthetic fiber ropes which typically employ in the mooring systems. Different guidelines provide different preload treatment such as American Petroleum Institute (API,


  2015


), International Standard Organization (ISO,


  2007


), Cordage Institute 1500 (CI 1500,


  2002


) and Det Norske Veritas and Germanischer Lloyd (DNVGL,


  2017


) as illustrated in

 Table 1

. MBL stands for minimum break load. It is clearly shown that all these guidelines provide different preload treatment in term of loading range and number of cycles. Nonetheless, preload treatment in tensile loading is not widely implemented and discussed.

